    "# Algorithms for ML and NLP\n",
    "\n",
    "## Outline:\n",
    "1. Algorithm complexity  \n",
    "2. Byte Pair Encoding  \n",
    "3. N-gram smoothing  \n",
    "4. Beam search  \n",
    "\n",
    "## Readings\n",
    "\n",
    "* Christopher Manning. Foundations of Statistical Natural Language Processing\n",
    "* (BPE) Philip Gage. A New Algorithm for Data Compression\n",
    "* (About n-gram smoothing 1) https://nlp.stanford.edu/~wcmac/papers/20050421-smoothing-tutorial.pdf\n",
    "* (About n-gram smoothing 2) https://web.stanford.edu/~jurafsky/slp3/3.pdf"

   "source": [
    "# 2 Byte Pair Encoding\n",
    "\n",
    "Problem of text tokenization:\n",
    "1. If tokenized per word => len(sequence) is moderate, but vocab_size >> 1\n",
    "2. If tokenized per chars => vocab_size is moderate, but len(sequence) >> 1\n",
    "\n",
    "Long sequences mean long training time,\n",
    "Big vocab size means more weighs in the models and potential overfitting.\n",
    "\n",
    "BPE, among others, is the \"middle ground\", trying to balance sequence length and vocab size by merging frequent n-grams into new tokens.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "AABCDCEABFABCB => vocab_size=6 => AB=X\n",
    "\n",
    "AXCDCEXFXCB => vocab_size=7 => XC=Y\n",
    "\n",
    "AYDCEXFYB => vocab_size=8\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**sketch for algorithm**:\n",
    "\n",
    "while (vocab) < max_vocab_size:\n",
    "1. count bigram frequencies\n",
    "1. take most common bigram $w_i,w_j$\n",
    "1. substitute it with a new token in the text\n",
    "1. update vocab"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 4 N-gram models for Language modeling\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"images/lm.png\" style=\"height:300px\">\n",
    "\n",
    "Probability of a sequence of tokens ${w_i}$:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "P(w_1, .., w_T) = P(w_1) P(w_2 | w_1) ... P(w_T | w_{1}, ..., w_{T-1})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "## Perplexity\n",
    "\n",
    "Common quality metric language modeling is perplexity (smaller is the better):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ Q(w_1, .., w_T) = P(w_1, .., w_T)^{-\\frac 1 T}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Perplexity of a corpus of text:\n",
    "\n",
    "As $$C = {s_1, .. , s_m}$$ then  $$P(c) = \\prod_{i=1}^m P(s_i)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ Q(C) = (\\prod_{i=1}^m P(s_i))^{- \\frac 1 m}  =\\\n",
    "2^{\\log_2 (\\prod_{i=1}^m P(s_i))^{- \\frac 1 m}}  =\\\n",
    "2^{- \\frac 1 m \\log_2 (\\prod_{i=1}^m P(s_i))} =\\\n",
    "2^{- \\frac 1 m \\sum_{i=1}^m log_2 P(s_i)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## N-gram models \n",
    "N-gram language model = (finite horizon):\n",
    "$$P(w_t | w_{1}, ..., w_{t-1}) = P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1})$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P(w_1, .., w_T) = \\prod_{t=1}^T P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1})$$\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "How to estimate $P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1})$?\n",
    "\n",
    "## Naive approach:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}) = \\frac {count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, w_t)} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, \\hat w)} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "OR\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}) = \\frac {count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, w_t)^{\\frac 1 \\tau}} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, \\hat w)^{\\frac 1 \\tau}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $tau$ is called temperature. Higher temperature means more flat probability distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Problems with naive approach?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Laplace smoothing\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}) = \\frac {count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, w_t) + \\delta} {\\sum_{\\hat w} [count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, \\hat w) + \\delta]} $$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\delta$ accounts for missing n-grams\n",
    "\n",
    "## Linear interpolation (for 3 grams)\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ P(w_3 | w_1, w_2) = \\lambda_3 \\frac {count(w_1, w_2, w_3)} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(w_1, w_2, \\hat w)} +\\\n",
    "\\lambda_2 \\frac {count(w_2, w_3)} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(w_2, \\hat w)} +\\\n",
    "\\lambda_1 \\frac {count(w_3)} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(\\hat w)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "General case, where $\\lambda$ is some hyperparam, $\\sum_i \\lambda_i = 1$\n",
    "\n",
    "## Kneser-Ney Smoothing\n",
    "\n",
    "$$P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}) = \\frac {max(0, count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, w_t) - \\delta} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, \\hat w) + \\delta}  + \\\n",
    "\\lambda_{w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}}  P(w_t | w_{t-n+2}, ..., w_{t-1})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where \n",
    "$$\\lambda_{w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}} =\\\n",
    "\\delta \\frac {| \\{ \\hat w:  count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, w_t) > 0 \\}|} {\\sum_{\\hat w} count(w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}, \\hat w)}$$ \n",
    "is a normalization constant\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The essence of Kneser-Ney is in an observation that we can take advantage of the interpolation as a backoff model. When the first term (the higher-order term) is near zero, the second term (the lower-order model) carries more weight. And vice versa.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 5 Beam Search\n",
    "\n",
    "Inference for Language Models: we would like to generate a new sequence of tokens from conditioned on some input. \n",
    "And usually we want the generated sequence to be the most probable for the input, and at the same time diverse enough not to collapse into the same mode.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "What's the time? -> I don't know.\n",
    "How are you? -> I don't know.\n",
    "...\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "* Naive:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ w_t = argmax P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}) $$\n",
    "\n",
    "However, greedy selecting the tokens not necessarily mean producing the most probable sequence.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Sample token from distribution\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ w_t \\sim P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}) $$\n",
    "\n",
    "* With temperature, controlling \"the randomness\" of generated sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ w_t \\sim P(w_t | w_{t-n+1}, ..., w_{t-1}; \\tau) $$\n",
    "\n",
    "* Beam search: greedy, but smarter.  \n",
    "On every iteration of token generation support $k$ top probable sequences\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"images/beam.png\" style=\"height:600px\">"
   ]
  },
